04558nam a22006255i 9780226585628DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265856287 a10.7208/97802265856282doi  a(DE-B1597)523280  a(OCoLC)1062360940  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBL65.P7b.Y455 2019 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a201/.722231 aYelle, Robert A., eauthor.10aSovereignty and the Sacred :bSecularism and the Political Economy of Religion /cRobert A. Yelle. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Antinomian Sacred as a Political Category: Toward a Theory of Religion as Sovereignty -- t2. The Disenchantment of Charisma: The Theological Origins of Secular Polity -- t3. The Ambivalence of the Sovereign Ban: The Homo Sacer and the Biblical Herem -- t4. Sacrifice, or the Religious Mode of Production -- t5. States of Nature: The Jubilee and the Social Contract -- t6. No Deposit, No Return: Religious Rejections of Exchange -- tConclusion: Exit Signs -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSovereignty and the Sacred challenges contemporary models of polity and economy through a two-step engagement with the history of religions. Beginning with the recognition of the convergence in the history of European political theology between the sacred and the sovereign as creating "states of exception"-that is, moments of rupture in the normative order that, by transcending this order, are capable of re-founding or remaking it-Robert A. Yelle identifies our secular, capitalist system as an attempt to exclude such moments by subordinating them to the calculability of laws and markets. The second step marshals evidence from history and anthropology that helps us to recognize the contribution of such states of exception to ethical life, as a means of release from the legal or economic order. Yelle draws on evidence from the Hebrew Bible to English deism, and from the Aztecs to ancient India, to develop a theory of polity that finds a place and a purpose for those aspects of religion that are often marginalized and dismissed as irrational by Enlightenment liberalism and utilitarianism. Developing this close analogy between two elemental domains of society, Sovereignty and the Sacred offers a new theory of religion while suggesting alternative ways of organizing our political and economic life. By rethinking the transcendent foundations and liberating potential of both religion and politics, Yelle points to more hopeful and ethical modes of collective life based on egalitarianism and popular sovereignty. Deliberately countering the narrowness of currently dominant economic, political, and legal theories, he demonstrates the potential of a revived history of religions to contribute to a rethinking of the foundations of our political and social order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aHoly, The. 0aReligion and politicsxHistory. 0aSecularism. 4aCarl Schmitt. 4aGiorgio Agamben. 4aJubilee. 4aMax Weber. 4acharisma. 4adisenchantment. 4arational choice theory. 4asacred. 4asacrifice. 4asovereignty. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226585628423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226585628.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles